</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65A7652EC07E4B1CFF014BC2FB1D32A6" box="[192,1194,1687,1714]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2D0236A5C07E4B1CFF014BC2FB1D32A6" blockId="31.[192,1194,1687,1714]" box="[192,1194,1687,1714]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C07E4B1CFF014BC2FEF332A6" bold="true" box="[192,324,1687,1713]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName id="EABD4D26C07E4B1CFDEF4BCDFDFA32A6" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[558,589,1688,1713]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rio">
<emphasis id="1FC9EAB7C07E4B1CFDEF4BCDFDFA32A6" box="[558,589,1688,1713]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">rio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a noun in apposition and refers to the 
<typeStatus id="F2068807C07E4B1CFBDD4BCDFBFB32A5" box="[1052,1100,1688,1714]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
